[
    "The Great Sphinx of Giza is carved directly from the natural **limestone bedrock** of the Giza Plateau[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [2](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v2d6sqmukFw), which belongs to the **Mokattam Formation** of Eocene age[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Sphinx_of_Giza).\n\nThis limestone was formed approximately 50 million years ago from carbonate mud that petrified over time[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/). Because the rock is not uniform, it is categorized into three distinct geological members, each with varying mineral durability and composition[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [4](https://egyptra.pro/sphinx-egypt):\n\n*   **Member I (Base):** The lowest layer, forming the Sphinx's base and paws, consists of hard, brittle, reef-derived limestone[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [4](https://egyptra.pro/sphinx-egypt).\n*   **Member II (Body):** The main body of the Sphinx is carved from this section, which consists of seven alternating layers of softer and harder limestone[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [4](https://egyptra.pro/sphinx-egypt). This variation in hardness is the primary reason for the uneven weathering and erosion seen on the statue's body today[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [4](https://egyptra.pro/sphinx-egypt).\n*   **Member III (Head and Neck):** The head is carved from a harder, more durable layer of limestone, which has helped preserve its features[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [4](https://egyptra.pro/sphinx-egypt). The neck, however, consists of a softer layer[1](https://aeraweb.org/geology-of-the-sphinx/), [4](https://egyptra.pro/sphinx-egypt).\n\n### Chemical and Mineralogical Factors in Deterioration\nBeyond the primary calcium carbonate (limestone) structure, studies on the deterioration of the Sphinx have identified the presence of other substances that affect its stability[5](https://www.hallofmaat.com/sphinx/deterioration-of-the-stone-of-the-great-sphinx/):\n*   **Water-soluble salts:** The limestone contains salts such as **halite** (sodium chloride) and **gypsum** (calcium sulfate dihydrate)[5](https://www.hallofmaat.com/sphinx/deterioration-of-the-stone-of-the-great-sphinx/). \n*   **Deterioration:** These salts contribute to the decay of the stone[5](https://www.hallofmaat.com/sphinx/deterioration-of-the-stone-of-the-great-sphinx/). Research has observed that halite is often more prevalent in the most deteriorated areas, as it easily dissolves and recrystallizes in the presence of moisture, causing the stone to flake and crumble[5](https://www.hallofmaat.com/sphinx/deterioration-of-the-stone-of-the-great-sphinx/).\n*   **Clastic components:** The rock also contains varying amounts of silt and clay minerals, which further influence how the stone reacts to environmental weathering[5](https://www.hallofmaat.com/sphinx/deterioration-of-the-stone-of-the-great-sphinx/)."
